And get session variable like

    case &#39;2&#39;:
      Session::get(&#39;data&#39;);
      Log::info(Session::get(&#39;data&#39;));

Try

    case &#39;1&#39;:       
    $phone = trim($explode[3]);
    $code = &#39;234&#39;
    $data = [
      &#39;passcode&#39; =&gt; $pass
    ];

    Session::put(&#39;data&#39;, $data);
    Session::save();
    Log::info(Session::get(&#39;data&#39;));

There is a difference between the `session.php` configuration file [`Config::set(&#39;session&#39;,...)`] and the actual session.  The configuration file is just for storing settings, and is not actually writable through inline changes.

See the documentation for proper usage:  
https://laravel.com/docs/6.x/session#using-the-session

The easiest method is probably the global session helper, `session()`.
```php
// Retrieve a piece of data from the session...
$value = session(&#39;key&#39;);

// Specifying a default value...
$value = session(&#39;key&#39;, &#39;default&#39;);

// Store a piece of data in the session...
session([&#39;key&#39; =&gt; &#39;value&#39;]);
```
Please note that the session is only written when a response is returned.  If you end a script prematurely, the session changes will not save unless done so explicitly.
```php
// force the session changes to be saved
session()-&gt;save();
```

